msItem.title: Capitula
msItem.incipit: iv recto: Incipiunt capitula libri subsequentis qui dicitur Brettoun
msItem.explicit: v verso: Expliciunt capitula Iibri subsequentis qui incipit hic.

msItem.title: Prologus
msItem.incipit: 1r: Edward par la grace dieu Roy dengleterre et sire de Irlaunde
msItem.explicit: 2v: en veue de franc plegge een autres courtz.

msItem.title: Britton
msItem.incipit: 3r: I. De Coroners. E pur ceo qe nous voloms qe coroners seient en chescun counte.
msItem.explicit: 136v: saunz jour iesqes al retourn de cely. Explicit.

foliation.note: Numbering in ink in upper right-hand corner of each leaf recto.
Leaf between 131 and 132 unfoliated; numbered 131A in pencil. Fols i-v, 137 numbered in pencil.

collation.p:
The manuscript comprises one quire composed of six leaves followed by fifteen quires of eight leaves. The last quire is made of ten leaves. There are leaves missing in quires a and 17, and some leaves are cancelled in quire 16. Folio i was formerly a pastedown, now lifted.
Quire a6-1 (ff. i recto-v verso: first leaf missing)
Quires 1-158 (ff. 1-122)
Quire 1610-2 (ff. 123-130: third and ninth leaves cancelled)
Quire 178-1 (ff. 131-137: last leaf missing)
collation.formula: a4-1 (1 missing) + 2 (ff. ii-iii inserted after 2) 1-158 1610-2 (3 and 9 cancelled) 178-1 (8 missing)

p.signatures: Quires numbered on recto of first leaf of each quire.

layout.seg: Single columns, lines, frame and lines ruled in ink, written below top line.

decoNote.p: Spaces left for initials with guide letters.

additions.note: Title written in a 17th-century hand on f. ii recto.

binding.p: 17th-century calfskin with blind-tooled concentric frames composed of double fillets and floral rolls, floral cornerpieces to inner frames. Rebacked in 20th century.

history.provenance: On iv recto and 136v is inscribed 'Liber Johannis May Cantuar'.

Late 16th/early 17th-century inscription on ii recto of
Joseph Wasse (1672-1739), clergyman and classical scholar, Queens' alumnus (matric. 1691) Wasse, Joseph, 1672-1738 : 'Sum Josephi Wasse et amicorum'.
history.acquisition:
Presented to the Library by
Joseph Wasse Wasse, Joseph, 1672-1738
in 1722. His gift is recorded in Queens' Donors' Book, p. 45.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on the description in M.R. James, A descriptive catalogue of the western manuscripts in the library of Queens’ College, Cambridge (Cambridge, 1905).

availability.p: For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact Queens' Old Library and Special Collections.
